{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ac04a4d4-c6ad-4868-92bd-2f979f89e2da","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool binary in via `kubectl cp`.\n- For production-safe, lower-overhead collection, use **`--profile cpu-sampling`** (default 10ms interval) — it's designed to be lightweight.\n- To get off-CPU / wait-time data too, use `dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile gc-collect` or pair with `perf` for native frames.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b928ee22-48f8-4023-9d59-3ccab1504b61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":338,"requestId":"6400:1BDA73:14C0577:181732E:69EC155B"},"id":"b0e18fa9-74ea-4919-af96-443bd3bf1a2d","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:14:12.347Z","parentId":"80e3db2a-5bd1-48e2-8817-70677c3db773"}
